Nieuwporte m Michel Ballego
In antw. den ul van 3 deser is mij wel gewoorden, hope het paecken n. 4
haest tot londen sal wesen. heden hebbe gesonden p bode nogh een van 't selve
merck n5, waer voors port gelieft te bet als het voorgaende, & stellen op reeg
aen m Edmund Warner, aen he welcken het selve met alle spoet gelieft te
depecheeren. hebbe alnogh gesonden t packet bestaende van 3 bleyne om daer
mede te volgen d'ord. van m Antonij Bosseau van Brussel, ul is gewent die sorte
te bet., soo hebbe met den bode niet geaccordeert, als alleen dat hy te mede is te
ontf. gelijck de boden van brussel voor de selve hebben tot costi daer is voorder nogh
1 packet gemerckt M.S.P. N°5 van mr. Jan Ba Baudier volgens den advis brief
daer beneffens sijnde, is het saecken dat ul voor de selve gewoon is de port te
bet soo gelieft het te doen all'ordinaire, soo niet sal op ul advijs de selve hier
beye mits het groot is, vraeghde den bode 2 pattaconse oversulckx sal deswegens

T la r Richard Southell
In answer to yo of 20 curr, I am glad you have had good sales all a long
his summer, though goods be deare, where there is good sall there musth be good
proffitt, yett by yo. I supose the contrary because you finde butt little incorridgne
do in large yo trade: what sower you do in my behalfe shall be well don
whilst neversheless att this yeares end I hope to finde yo. acctt. to content
noth withostanding the news of prolongation of the king of frenck demands
wee are still allarmed, &our contray people, hath no inclisnation to buy,
goods, much less to pait of their mony which is confirmed by the daylys
marching of souldiens, which draw toghether from all parts, what their
intention is, God knows, the hollanders are with 8000 in march to, so that
wee hope to maintaine our aight by force, whilst wee are in the meanetinae
in a rewpoore condition of trade. I should have drawne on you this day beett
could do ne less then 14 loss for 21so, which I am loast to do, though my
occasion is miglhtie vrgent, to shall de lay as long as scan strive
The 4ld chicolatte is on itts way with father egant packett, yd ledder is
delivered him, & when I know what remiss have shall now you bonth, this
chocolatte cost 4ostivers a found 7 at for S. scamand I hope so recover most
part or all, I have inderstood the tie is gon to see his facher in hopes to
have mony from him to pay lus dibt, & so to returne to England of tewad
whit honouw Iwhandes what you lay of m Collius, he payd 19 ƒ for the
cronicle & whould have nothing of mee for ytt, for aferrwards whire I whoubd
allowitt him apon acctt. he whald he would not, for he disburst the silk hese
& some hotts, & otked, small baggatells for which I gave his sacher cred. in the
while, why would he have mee pay itt noow, which I so lough sence have
estemeed a giss. I made pasf the £19:10- for laces to his packer pray tell
hun that he must not rember agist, brutt lett mee remeiber itt to neward
which I then promised to do
London Michiel peeters
Antwerpen 5 gb 1681 103
mons. op 28 passato was aen ul mijnen lesten, sedert geene van ul. ten langhen
leften, nae dat ulrweder alveele dagen hier in stadt heeft geweest, sonder
bij mij te comen hebben wij de Rek corant gesloten, volgens de selve hier in geleyt
aen ul sende, waer onderstaet sijn dischargee nu tot u satisfactie, ende onser
bejde gerustigheyt sende die aen ul, op dat ul deselve gelieft te approbeeren
ende de betaling te ordonneeren aen mr. slanghter ul gelieft het op dese
medegaende Reke te doen doen not arialijk, in presentie van getuygen inder
manieren als hier ingeleyt apart gescreven, ts ende aen mij terugge senden
ul kan daer een copie van houden ick doen u goet £20: voor ul hebft
inde bekennde gastos seere tos 1679 ende £86: 13:4 voor £50: st a 34: 8 dewel
het eenigh erreur oft omittering is geweest in alle de voorgaende Rek. soo dat
ul mach vrijelijk gerust sijn oock moet ul verlekert sijn dat ick mijn
consiente voor een hants vol gelt niet wille beswaert late, ende dat ick
iets wiste anders het geirne soude vergoeden: nu omtedoonen dat het
aen mij niets gemanckert en heeft ul dienste te doen, soo sal ick m. chought
voldoen als ul bijden ingesloten kan lesen nochtans daer sijn noch wel
ƒ9 a ƒ5000 uytstaende sulden maerten sij ick in alles manieren & dischargee
ben niet hebbe, bij provisie 12 lakens heden afgesonden volgens de facture
oock ingesloten, de welke same met den brief aen mr. slanghter gelieft ter
handt de stellen ende pr naeste van alles advies tegeven, want de lakens
tot brugge aen mijn ordre sullen blijven liggen, tot u antwoort ick wenste
wel dat m slanghter teverden was met de volgende presentatie, oock soo
haest bij mijn presentatie aen nemt, soo moet hij u van alles ontlasten
en alle arresten te niet doen op dat destilderijen en andere konnen, daer
het moet wesen, geimployeert worden waer toe u broeder mij seer heeft
versoeht d'welk diene ul tot advies van u broeder heeft noch 4 lakens doen

Sr. I supose, that you do much wonder, where the cloathes of m. peeters are detained
so come now to give you an acctt. of what hetherto I have don, as well in yd as
their behalfe in the first I have fomd that itt was impossible for them
to pay yd rest sooner neither can they do itt yett, except by my assistance
& disbourse which I am willing to do, to make an end to that affaire
though there is much instanding out debts, for I have sold some of the
cloathes & what elee I have hadd for them to sell, except 12 peeces of
theij are
which incloled is the invoyce, amonting to £
vere good goods for their prijses, andam sure the like goodness would yeald
now with you is more considdered by what I duyly receave from
England, so that itt is onely the cullour that is amis on them, which doubths
you will be able to putt off for other countreys, att this rate, if att in
bringiny them from englandhither, & sence so long time unsold & now
againe to returne them att their charge, where fore & finde itt apr of
conscience to abate any thing on the frirst cost & desire you to take them
att those prijses as they cost & desice you toetane t
are noted yn the inclosed invoyce they beeng sent forward this day to bruges
in a bale M: this I must intreal you to do from yd defire side which in case
son condeseend to then Ell remitt you the rest in mony which is as much
as you, or they can exspect from afreind & do not exspett yd refuse
because j iudge that there can ben loss up on the goods & thoughthere should
be any, itt will bevere little for each of the interresved & much tond neeters I which
do vere little much complaine, that all a long you have secured yd self in lond
of their Effects there as well as here they haveing suffered much there by
so you must then discharge yds arrest yett upndondition that m
michiell t peeters signes & approves mi att, as well as his brother Antori
hath don which I leave to you to see performed, because what I do love to be
to be approve off as well don, & principplly now & in this bussynes, where
part from them. I have no more to inlarge butt to assure you that
what I write you is really minded & because of intercession of freind
shall be performed, so that I exspect yd acceptance so first, for if itt
awere for my owne self, I could do no more & so remaine
